                     <handNote xml:id="h1" script="Ethiopic">
                        <seg type="script">Mediocre</seg>
                        <seg type="ink">Black, red</seg>
                        <date>19th century</date>
                        <list type="abbreviations">
                           <item>
                              <abbr>ለ፡ ዓ፡ አ፡</abbr> for <expan>ለዓለመ፡ ዓለም፡ አሜን፡ </expan> (e.g.,
                                 <locus target="#70vb">70vb</locus>)</item>
                           <item>
                              <abbr>ለዓ፡ ዓለ፡ አሜን፡</abbr> for <expan>ለዓለመ፡ ዓለም፡ አሜን፡ </expan> (e.g.,
                                 <locus target="#72vb">72vb</locus>)</item>
                        </list>
                        
                        <note>The scribe interrupted on <locus target="#30va">30va</locus> and started
                           again on <locus target="#31ra">31ra</locus> probably leaving the space for
                           the miniature.</note>
                        
                        <seg type="rubrication">Holy names; a few lines on the incipit page of all
                           sections (alternating with black lines); incipits of all subsections;
                           each second letter in the initial lines of the Additio; elements of the
                           punctuation signs and of the text dividers; elements of Ethiopic
                           numerals.</seg>
                     </handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h2" script="Ethiopic">The handwriting is characterized by a
                        broad, rounded and upright (or slightly left-sloping) script with
                        distinctive
                        features:</handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h3" script="Ethiopic"> - many letters have hairlines, esp. at
                        the top (e.g., ለ, ረ, ሰ, ት,
                        ዕ)</handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h4" script="Ethiopic"> - some letters have forked elements
                        (e.g., ኀ, ተ )
                        </handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h5" script="Ethiopic"> - the characters መ and ሠ in all vowel
                        orders are often set on the baseline (e.g., <locus target="#18vb">18vb</locus>)</handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h6" script="Ethiopic"> - the letters እ and ለ are sometimes
                        difficult to distinguish (e.g., <locus target="#19ra">19ra</locus>
                        <locus target="#14">14</locus> against <locus target="#81vb">81vb</locus>
                        l.5)</handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h7" script="Ethiopic"> - the vowel markers of ዮ and ድ are
                        often attached at the very top of the letter's body (e.g., <locus target="#81va">81va</locus>b,
                        110ra).</handNote>
                  </handDesc>
